\begin{align*} 
\text{Third equation: } \quad & \left( 121 + cd \right) \left( c + d \right) = 169c + 81d\\
\Rightarrow \quad & c^2 + 121c + cd^2 + 121d = 169c + 81d\\ 
\Rightarrow \quad & c^2 - 48c + cd^2 - 40d = 0
\end{align*}
Adding the left sides and right sides of the three equations:
\begin{align*} 
LHS &= a^2 + b^2 + c^2 - 96(a + b + c)\\  
RHS &= -96(a + b + c)
\end{align*}
Since $LHS = RHS$, we have:
\begin{align*}
a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 0
\end{align*}
The fourth equation gives: 
\begin{align*}
a + b + c + d = 12
\end{align*}
Plugging $d = m - \sqrt{n}$ into the fourth equation and simplifying using $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 0$:
\begin{align*}
m - \sqrt{n} = 12 - (a + b + c) = \pm\sqrt{a^2 + b^2 + c^2} = 0
\end{align*}
Therefore, $m - \sqrt{n} = 0 \Rightarrow m = \sqrt{n}$.
Squaring both sides: 
$m^2 = n$
